   "source": [
    "# Modeling\n",
    "\n",
    "*prose* does not implement a modeling framework, many options are currently available in python. However, it features some tools to aid in selecting the right model, mainly linear ones.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial we will review some of these tools and show how the prose products can conveniently be used within [exoplanet](https://docs.exoplanet.codes/en/latest/), itself using the [pymc3](https://docs.pymc.io/en/v3/index.html) inference framework."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "588b014f-5b90-4c24-ae08-15a7751d8422",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "\n",
    "Tutorial requirements:\n",
    "<ul>\n",
    "    <li>exoplanet</li>\n",
    "    <li>pymc3_ext</li>\n",
    "    <li>corner</li>\n",
    "</ul>\n",
    "    \n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "banner-withdrawal",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Making up some data\n",
    "\n",
    "As usual we will work on synthetic data. Here we propose to analyse a planetary transit light curve in which we added some instrumental signals:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "renewable-stomach",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-07-19T17:16:30.036620Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-07-19T17:16:30.036300Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.293615Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.293352Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\u001b[38;5;12mINFO\u001b[0m Could not convert time to BJD TDB\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from prose.simulations import observation_to_model\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(37)\n",
    "\n",
    "time = np.linspace(0, 0.3, 300)\n",
    "obs = observation_to_model(time)\n",
    "obs.plot()\n",
    "_ = plt.ylim(0.98, 1.02)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "exposed-maine",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "\n",
    "Note\n",
    "\n",
    "In what follows we will consider that we already have a good knowledge of our transit parameters. This is for the tutorial's purpose and one can adapt it by adjusting the model's priors (especially in the inference part).\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "adequate-trademark",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Linear models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "described-retrieval",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Polynomial systematics"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "precise-messaging",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is common to model the instrumental signals using a linear model involving some systematic measurements. Let's say that we measured an explanatory variable $\\boldsymbol{x}$ along time (the temperature of the detector for example). If $\\boldsymbol{f}$ is our measured flux sampled along the same time, we can suppose that it can be modeled as a polynomial order 2 of $\\boldsymbol{x}$ plus some **gaussian** noise, so that:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\boldsymbol{f} = a\\boldsymbol{x}^2 + b\\boldsymbol{x} +  c + \\boldsymbol{\\epsilon}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$a$, $b$, $c$ being free parameters. This can be writen in the matrix form:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\boldsymbol{f} =\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}a & b & c\\end{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix} \\boldsymbol{\\phantom{,}x^2}\\\\\\boldsymbol{x}\\\\\\boldsymbol{1}\\end{pmatrix} = \n",
    "wX$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with $X$ the *design matrix*. $X$ is known so that this linear equation can be solved for $w$ through ordinary least square. Before doing any of that let's make sure our observation is clean"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "timely-strengthening",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.295375Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.295284Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.299937Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.299680Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# removing obvious outlier\n",
    "obs = obs.sigma_clip()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "mental-veteran",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can now use *prose* methods to build a linear model by defining its *design matrix* $X$. Here we decided to set an order 2 polynomial of the sky data to start with"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "eastern-luxembourg",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.301405Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.301325Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.366069Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.365844Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from prose import models\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "X = models.polynomial(obs.sky, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "trend = obs.lstsq(X)\n",
    "\n",
    "obs.plot()\n",
    "plt.plot(obs.time, trend)\n",
    "_ = plt.ylim(0.98, 1.02)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "attended-analysis",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Although it's not very good, the model is certainly not complete. Let's make it better."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "informational-politics",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Adding a transit\n",
    "\n",
    "Our data contain a transit signal which, at first order, can be modeled as a scaled transit of unitary depth. To do that we will add this template to our design matrix. Here, we will use the more conveniant `Observation.polynomial()` method which comes handy for more complex models."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "activated-shoulder",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.367931Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.367797Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.370797Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.370495Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "t0 = 0.1\n",
    "duration = 0.05\n",
    "\n",
    "X = np.hstack([\n",
    "    obs.polynomial(sky=1, dy=1),\n",
    "    obs.transit(t0, duration)\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Notice the use of split to get the transit model\n",
    "trend, transit = obs.lstsq(X, split=-1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "honest-auditor",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {

     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.433694Z"
    }

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "romance-promise",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Model selection\n",
    "\n",
    "In the last sections we used arbitrary models of the systematics. It seems the last one is complete and not too complex but wiser choice can be made using model selection crtieria like [BIC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_information_criterion)\n",
    "or [AIC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akaike_information_criterion). Here we will iterate on a range of possible models and compute which one gives the best BIC:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "polar-dubai",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.435650Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.435568Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.448477Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.448213Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "best model: {'sky': 1, 'dy': 2}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# we authorize combinations up to order 5\n",
    "\n",
    "best = obs.best_polynomial(sky=5, dy=5, add=obs.transit(t0, duration))\n",
    "print(\"best model:\", best)"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "figured-seeking",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "We will now use [exoplanet](https://docs.exoplanet.codes/en/stable/)  to infer of our transit parameters. For this part of the tutorial you will need [exoplanet](https://docs.exoplanet.codes/en/stable/) and [corner](https://corner.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) to be installed."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "remarkable-animation",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The basic principle of `pymc3` is to let you define free parameters distributions and specify the models which depend on them before doing any computation. Doing so, a pre-optimized graph is built **once** making any later execution much faster. This comes handy for inference since a lot of  samples need to be drawn from your posterior distribution. Let's build our `pymc3` model with `exoplanet` (lot more details [here](https://docs.exoplanet.codes/en/stable/tutorials/transit/)):"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "featured-quality",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.536888Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-07-19T17:16:32.536812Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-07-19T17:18:16.335952Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-07-19T17:18:16.335237Z"
    }
   },

   "source": [
    "# here we use exoplanet 0.5.2\n",
    "\n",
    "import pymc3 as pm\n",
    "import pymc3_ext as pmx\n",
    "import exoplanet as xo\n",
    "from prose.utils import earth2sun\n",
    "\n",
    "with pm.Model() as model:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Transit parameters\n",
    "    # ------------------\n",
    "    period = pm.Uniform(\"period\", 0.1, 3)\n",
    "    r = pm.Uniform(\"r\", 3, 8)*earth2sun\n",
    "    w = pm.Flat(\"s\", len(X.T), testval=np.linalg.lstsq(X, obs.diff_flux, rcond=None)[0])\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Keplerian orbit\n",
    "    # ---------------\n",
    "    orbit = xo.orbits.KeplerianOrbit(period=period, t0=0.1)\n",
    "    # starry light-curve\n",
    "    light_curves = xo.LimbDarkLightCurve([0.1, 0.4]).get_light_curve(orbit=orbit, r=r, t=obs.time)\n",
    "    transit = pm.Deterministic(\"transit\", pm.math.sum(light_curves, axis=-1))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Systematics and final model\n",
    "    # ---------------------------\n",
    "    systematics = X@w\n",
    "    mu = pm.Deterministic(\"mu\", transit + systematics)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Likelihood\n",
    "    # ----------\n",
    "    pm.Normal(\"obs\", mu=mu, sd=obs.diff_error, observed=obs.diff_flux)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Maximum a posteriori\n",
    "    # --------------------\n",
    "    opt = pmx.optimize(start=model.test_point)"
   ]
  },
